         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve">
        <p>
          Called the earliest Greco-Roman graphic novel, this illustrated papyrus features a dialogue between two interlocutors, one of whom is the famous Hercules. The other interlocutor challenges the great Hercules to describe his labors while promising to reveal what Heracles actually did through a series of
          <emph rend="italics">grulloi</emph>
          , "images". Because previous editions show substantial variations, ranging from omitted words or lines to unnecessary substitutions, a new edition was called for. The present edition compiles the previous editions, noting variations from those publications.
        </p>
      </div>
